00:38:28.760 --> 00:38:33.640
because obvoiusly this is
not an exercise in trying

00:38:33.640 --> 00:38:35.800
to replicate the medieval past,

00:38:35.800 --> 00:38:39.370
which we would argue is
probably somewhat futile

00:38:39.370 --> 00:38:42.960
because we cannot replicate
those conditions whatsoever.

00:38:42.960 --> 00:38:47.150
Our purposes are totally different,
but we did try and get close

00:38:47.150 --> 00:38:48.920
to ingredients like the wine.

00:38:48.920 --> 00:38:53.340
The honey was sourced from
[inaudible], a lady in Surrey

00:38:53.340 --> 00:39:00.000
who had recreated a medieval garden
with medicinal herbs and plants

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:03.590
and bees nearby were
pollinating those plants.

00:39:03.590 --> 00:39:06.220
So that's where we
obtained the honey from.

00:39:06.220 --> 00:39:08.820
And just for some continuity.

00:39:10.490 --> 00:39:11.790
Yes.

00:39:11.790 --> 00:39:13.940
&gt;&gt; I have two questions.

00:39:13.940 --> 00:39:17.460
One was in your studies did
you find that the formula --

00:39:17.460 --> 00:39:20.770
Bald's formula -- was
bactericidal or bacteriostatic?

00:39:20.770 --> 00:39:26.240 position:56%
And the other one is I'm kind of
mystified by the nine day shelf life

00:39:26.240 --> 00:39:29.270
or the -- actually I'd like
to know the shelf life.

00:39:29.270 --> 00:39:32.120
Once it reached the nine day,
was it potent on nine days?

00:39:32.120 --> 00:39:36.020
Which was probably just
serendipitously discovered.

00:39:36.020 --> 00:39:37.980
&gt;&gt; Erin Connelly: Trial
and error, yeah.

00:39:37.980 --> 00:39:41.960
&gt;&gt; And how long was it
good for thereafter?

00:39:41.960 --> 00:39:43.260
&gt;&gt; Erin Connelly: Yes.

00:39:43.260 --> 00:39:48.670
So I'm not a Ph.D. microbiologist.

00:39:48.670 --> 00:39:51.140
But I'm going to answer this.

00:39:51.140 --> 00:39:55.580
I will recommend that you
look to the paper as well

00:39:55.580 --> 00:39:59.640
and anything I don't
answer, contact Fred Harrison

00:39:59.640 --> 00:40:03.070
or Steve Digel whose email
addresses are on the paper.

00:40:03.070 --> 00:40:04.700
And they'll be happy to answer it.

00:40:04.700 --> 00:40:08.710
So the question for those who
didn't hear it was Bald's eyesalve

00:40:08.710 --> 00:40:12.060
bacteriocidal or bacteristatic?

00:40:12.060 --> 00:40:16.330
And the answer that's coming to me
from the paper is bacteriocidal,

00:40:16.330 --> 00:40:23.870
and in the results as well it was
found the word design has actually

00:40:23.870 --> 00:40:27.270
been used in reference
to this recipe.

00:40:27.270 --> 00:40:31.870
In that it treats the
infection that it was designed

00:40:31.870 --> 00:40:34.830
to treat almost in a targeted way.

00:40:34.830 --> 00:40:40.430
And the eyesalve has been
tested against other pathogens

00:40:40.430 --> 00:40:47.530 position:56%
such as K pneumoniae and E. coli and
Enterobacter and things like that.

00:40:47.530 --> 00:40:51.290
And the activity is different
so it's not like dumping bleach

00:40:51.290 --> 00:40:53.530
on something where it
just kills everything.

00:40:53.530 --> 00:40:57.290 position:56%
It seems to be specifically targeted
to what it was made to treat,

00:40:57.290 --> 00:41:00.440 position:56%
which is very interesting and worthy

00:41:00.440 --> 00:41:04.000
of more research and
that is ongoing.

00:41:04.000 --> 00:41:06.990
And then the other question was --

00:41:06.990 --> 00:41:11.450
was the eyesalve good for
the entire nine day period?

00:41:11.450 --> 00:41:13.360
What was its activity
through that period

00:41:13.360 --> 00:41:15.860
and how long does it stay good?

00:41:15.860 --> 00:41:18.810
That is actually being
looked at at the moment.

00:41:18.810 --> 00:41:23.550
There have been some old samples of
the eyesalve that are being tested.

00:41:23.550 --> 00:41:26.740
I was actually just speaking
to the microbiologist

00:41:26.740 --> 00:41:30.260
who performed this work,
and she had some old samples

00:41:30.260 --> 00:41:31.560
that they're testing.

00:41:31.560 --> 00:41:36.840
So I'm not sure about the terminal
dates, how long it stays good.

00:41:36.840 --> 00:41:42.420
I believe it has been tested, but
I can't give it's bad after 30 days

00:41:42.420 --> 00:41:45.510
or it becomes toxic
after this period.

00:41:45.510 --> 00:41:48.530
[ Inaudible ]

00:41:48.530 --> 00:41:49.830
At room temperature.

00:41:49.830 --> 00:41:52.460
And that was a consideration
in running this test.

00:41:52.460 --> 00:41:57.170
There were a lot of decisoins that
had to be made and it was decided

00:41:57.170 --> 00:42:02.470 position:56%
to keep the eyesalve in the
refrigerator because in the building

00:42:02.470 --> 00:42:05.600
where the lab was, the
heat comes on and off.

00:42:05.600 --> 00:42:08.020
And it was decided that
fluctuations in temperature

00:42:08.020 --> 00:42:11.100
like that would be more
unrealistic then keeping it

00:42:11.100 --> 00:42:16.310
at a steady temperature because
often in other medieval recipes --

00:42:16.310 --> 00:42:20.850
actually the one with
macular degeneration,

00:42:20.850 --> 00:42:25.400
one of the instructions says
make it as hot as a hen's nest

00:42:25.400 --> 00:42:29.150
when she's sitting on a nest.

00:42:29.150 --> 00:42:31.120
What temperature would that be?

00:42:31.120 --> 00:42:38.320
So I'll find a hen or -- so
that is during the winter.

00:42:38.320 --> 00:42:41.960
If it's being made during the
summer, the recipe is to sit

00:42:41.960 --> 00:42:46.260
in a cool dark shadow so it's what
they had in their environment,

00:42:46.260 --> 00:42:48.580
but they're looking for
a steady temperature.

00:42:48.580 --> 00:42:52.830
With the hen, steady temperature,
dark shadow, steady temperature.

00:42:52.830 --> 00:42:55.400
So that's why we chose
refrigeration.

00:42:55.400 --> 00:42:57.190
Yes.

00:42:57.190 --> 00:43:01.120
&gt;&gt; You mentioned that one of the
things that you discovered is

00:43:01.120 --> 00:43:04.780
that the Bald's eyesalve recipe for
instance is highly reproducible.

00:43:04.780 --> 00:43:07.650
You can make the same
thing again and again.

00:43:07.650 --> 00:43:13.050
Is there any intent to try making
the recipe with modern wine

00:43:13.050 --> 00:43:15.690
and honey since those two
ingredients seem to be

00:43:15.690 --> 00:43:19.300
so much limited in availability?

00:43:19.300 --> 00:43:21.870
&gt;&gt; Erin Connelly: Well, we could
say it was made with modern wine

00:43:21.870 --> 00:43:27.740
and honey because we don't
really have access --

00:43:27.740 --> 00:43:31.630
all of these ingredients are
modern in the sense that --

00:43:31.630 --> 00:43:33.660
sorry, for those who
didn't hear the question,

00:43:33.660 --> 00:43:38.670
it was has there been any
attempt to perhaps change the wine

00:43:38.670 --> 00:43:43.650
and honey other then the ones
that we used in the original test?

00:43:43.650 --> 00:43:45.210
Yeah, okay.

00:43:45.210 --> 00:43:50.000
No. It's -- well with the
six who have reproduced it,

00:43:50.000 --> 00:43:55.470
I'm not entirely sure if they
used the exact same sources,

00:43:55.470 --> 00:43:57.050
although I think they did

00:43:57.050 --> 00:44:00.820
because they were trying
to replicate it exactly.

00:44:00.820 --> 00:44:04.770
I know that in the recipe
that I made with the cold

00:44:04.770 --> 00:44:09.760
and flu preventative I changed
the honey multiple times,

00:44:09.760 --> 00:44:14.400
and we still need to
test this, but I will say

00:44:14.400 --> 00:44:19.070
that Manuka honey would be
worth trialing in one of these

00:44:19.070 --> 00:44:23.490
because it is -- it has the highest
antimicrobial content of any honey.

00:44:23.490 --> 00:44:29.040
And it's what I use in my recipe.

00:44:29.040 --> 00:44:33.000
Maybe it's a placebo effect
because I really believe in it.

00:44:33.000 --> 00:44:36.670
But that waits to be seen.

00:44:36.670 --> 00:44:43.370 position:56%
Yeah, because often medieval recipes
-- even with vinegar and with wine,

00:44:43.370 --> 00:44:48.030
they'll say make it a weak
wine, make it a strong vinegar.

00:44:48.030 --> 00:44:52.390
Sometimes they don't give a lot
of guidance to what that means.

00:44:52.390 --> 00:44:56.240
Obviously with a weak wine, you
would think perhaps it's newly made

00:44:56.240 --> 00:45:00.320
or they're diluting it with
water or some other ingredients.

00:45:00.320 --> 00:45:04.220
But yeah, did that answer?

00:45:04.220 --> 00:45:08.240
&gt;&gt; To a certain extent, but one of
the things that I was more curious

00:45:08.240 --> 00:45:13.140
about is if these recipes
prove to be efficacious,

00:45:13.140 --> 00:45:17.950
then in order to ramp up
production you have to be able

00:45:17.950 --> 00:45:22.620
to source ingredients on a
mass scale, and it seems to me

00:45:22.620 --> 00:45:28.640
that a small vineyard [inaudible]
a local bee keeper aren't going

00:45:28.640 --> 00:45:31.870
to serve for mass production.

00:45:31.870 --> 00:45:33.170
&gt;&gt; Erin Connelly: No, no.

00:45:33.170 --> 00:45:37.110
In that case, we would have
to find a different source.

00:45:37.110 --> 00:45:43.610 position:56%
And I would -- I would say Manuka
is one of the best that we could do.

00:45:43.610 --> 00:45:47.240
But no, that tiny vineyard
and the poor bee keeper,

00:45:47.240 --> 00:45:52.160
no for worldwide production, but
of course we're not there yet.

00:45:52.160 --> 00:45:59.730
That was mainly done for the sake
of the pilot study and to keep it

00:45:59.730 --> 00:46:04.380
as close to the Anglosaxon
source as possible.

00:46:04.380 --> 00:46:09.340
And also because no one
expected it to be so effective.

00:46:09.340 --> 00:46:13.050
It was what we could call
a Friday afternoon project.

00:46:13.050 --> 00:46:17.080
Everybody did this
in their spare time,

00:46:17.080 --> 00:46:19.220
kind of still doing it that way.

00:46:19.220 --> 00:46:25.550
And it was really quite shocking
when these results came back

00:46:25.550 --> 00:46:31.300
and right now the recipe --
we're looking into the mechanism

00:46:31.300 --> 00:46:33.630
and action and that kind of thing.

00:46:33.630 --> 00:46:36.870
But its effects on human
cells need to be looked

00:46:36.870 --> 00:46:41.140
at first before we
look at anything else.

00:46:41.140 --> 00:46:42.640
Thank you.

00:46:42.640 --> 00:46:44.210
Yes.

